Introduction

GitHub: https://github.com/jerrayhan/320FinalProject

Dataset: Kaggle - U.S. Logistics Performance Dataset

With the rise of e-commerce, in recent years consumer and business demand for shipping services, especially expedited, has sky-rocketed. Consumers purchase goods more frequently than ever before and businesses compete to keep up with demand. Analysis of shipment logistics data may provide information about current operations, and provide valuable insight into how to streamline operations. This project utilizes a simulated shipping logistics dataset for analysis.

The goal of the following data processing, exploratory analysis, and machine learning analysis and visualization is to provide actionable insights for customers and businesses on factors that affect shipping efficiency. Specifically, we want to investigate how carrier choice, shipment cost, and seasonal timing influence transit efficiency. This can help customers make more informed decisions when choosing carriers based on speed, cost, and seasonal performance, as well as provide businesses with information that could help increase efficiency.

This dataset was chosen because it provides a wide variety of numerical and categorical features that allow for meaningful analysis of carrier logistics performance across the U.S.

Data Preprocessing

Our project focuses on the dataset found here: Kaggle - U.S. Logistics Performance Dataset.

This is a simulated dataset containing information on 2,000 U.S. shipment records. It is designed to represent real-world logistics operations, including intentional outliers (3%) and missing values (2%) to mimic data imperfections that commonly occur in real business contexts.

Each data point represents a single shipment with information about its origin warehouse, destination, carrier, shipment date, delivery date, package weight, cost, delivery status, distance in miles, and transit days.

Before analysis, we aim to, import necessary packages, organize the data into a Pandas Dataframe, and clean the data to prepare it for analysis.

The following data cleaning was written with our three hypotheses in mind in order to set the dataset up for smooth statistical testing. Dropping missing values and ensuring dates are in a format suitable for comparison and analysis helps with testing. Necessary columns have been added using information from other columns for our hypothesis tests and related outliers (for cost and transit distance per day) have also been removed.

In[]:
# Changes statuses to only two possible outcomes: 'Delivered' or 'Not Delivered' (replaced 'Lost', 'Delayed', 'In Transit')
df['Status'] = df['Status'].apply(lambda x: 'Delivered' if x=='Delivered' else 'Not Delivered')

# Transit distance per day
df['Transit_Distance_per_Day'] = df['Distance_miles']/df['Transit_Days']

# Remove cost outliers and transit distance per day outliers only
df = df[
    (df['Cost'] < df['Cost'].quantile(0.99)) &
    (df['Transit_Distance_per_Day'] < df['Transit_Distance_per_Day'].quantile(0.99))
].copy()


# Extracts the season and adds it based on SHIPMENT DAY
def get_season(date):
    month = date.month
    if month in [12, 1, 2]:
        return 'Winter'
    elif month in [3, 4, 5]:
        return 'Spring'
    elif month in [6, 7, 8]:
        return 'Summer'
    else:
        return 'Fall'

df['Season'] = df['Shipment_Date'].apply(get_season)

Hypothesis 1:

For our first hypothesis, we wanted to test the reliability between the different carriers. We will compare two categorical variables, the carrier & status through use of a Chi-Square test.

Null (H0): Carrier and delivery success rate are independent (success rate is equal across carriers).

Alternative (HA): Carrier and delivery success rate are not independent (some carriers are more successful than others).

In[]:
# code for chi square test
contingency = pd.crosstab(df['Carrier'], df['Status'])
chi2, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency)
print(f"Chi-Square Stat: {chi2}, p-val: {p}")

Chi-Square Stat: 5.151562479377576, p-val: 0.5245264118707864
In[]:
# code for graph (stacked bar graph)
contingency_norm = contingency.div(contingency.sum(axis=1), axis=0)

colors = ['#FFB6C1', '#FF69B4']
ax = contingency_norm.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10,6), color=colors)

for p in ax.patches:
    width, height = p.get_width(), p.get_height()
    x, y = p.get_xy()
    ax.text(x + width/2, y + height/2, f"{height*100:.1f}%", ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='white', fontweight='bold')

plt.ylabel("Proportion")
plt.xlabel("Carrier")
plt.title("Delivery Success Rate by Carrier", fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xticks(rotation=0)
plt.legend(title='Status', labels=['Delivered', 'Not Delivered'])

plt.show()

Hypothesis 1 Conclusion

Using a significance level of alpha = 0.05, our chi-square test of independence has resulted in a p-value of p=0.52452, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Additionally, there is a chi-square stat of 5, which falls on the lower end indicating a smaller difference between observed data.

This means that there is no statistical evidence that delivery success rate depends on the carrier. In other words, all carriers appear to have similar delivery reliability in this dataset. This is evident in our graph above, where it seems that the bars are around the same level for each carrier.

Even though we have not found a significant difference between carriers in terms of success, we can further explore how different factors such as cost and seasons affect performance. This is shown in the next two hypothesis.

Hypothesis 2:

To further investigate if cost per shipment is related to transit efficiency, we use a pearson correlation and scatter plot to visualize and test if higher cost shipments move faster.

Null (H0): Cost per shipment is unrelated to transit efficiency (distance per day).

Alternative (HA): Higher-cost shipments are faster (higher transit distance per day).

In[]:
# code for pearson correlation
r, p = pearsonr(df['Cost'], df['Transit_Distance_per_Day'])
print(f"Pearson Correlation: {r:.3f}, p-value: {p}")

Pearson Correlation: 0.606, p-value: 1.059844600490084e-189

Conclusion for Hypothesis 2:

Using a significance level of alpha = 0.05, our pearson correlation test has resulted in a p-value of p = 1.059844600490084e-189, so we reject the null hypothesis.

This shows a strong positive relationship between shipment cost and transit efficiency. In other words, more expensive shipments tend to move faster, which aligns with the intuition that a faster delivery can be induced by paying more.

Hypothesis 3:

To investigate carrier performance, we analyze their performance across season and check over their transit efficiency. Since we compare many groups (carriers), we use a Two-way ANOVA test as well as Tukey Post-Hoc. Through the post-hoc, we get to look at localized differences between carrier and season.

Null (H0): Carrier performance does not depend on the season (transit efficiency is consistent throughout the year).

Alternative (HA): Carrier performance depends on the season.

In[]:
# code for two-way anova
model = ols('Transit_Distance_per_Day ~ C(Carrier) + C(Season) + C(Carrier):C(Season)', data=df).fit()
anova_table = sm.stats.anova_lm(model, typ=2)
print(anova_table)

                          groups=df['Carrier_Season'],

Conclusion for Hypothesis 3

Using a significance level of alpha = 0.05, our two-way ANOVA test has resulted in p-values of {Carrier: p = 0.927; Season: p = 0.283; Carrier x Season: p = 0.549}, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis for all three categories.

This means that, statistically, there is no significant evidence that season affects transit efficiency across all carriers. However, visually looking at the graph we can notice that certain carriers, such as Amazon and OnTrac, tend to do much better in the summer than the winter, though the difference is neglible enough to not be statistically significant. Thought we failed to reject our null, the graph can still serve as a useful tool for noticing discrepancies across carrier performance based on season.

EDA Conclusion

The Exploratory Data Analysis section of this report aimed to break down the U.S logistics performance and analyze the dataset and highlight any relationships and patterns that have the potential to derive useful insights that can contribue to logistics decisions and strategies that pertain to carrier instances.

Insights

  1. Carrier Reliability
  • By a Chi-Square Test, it was determined that the differences were leveled and insignificant being over the alpha value (p > 0.05) throughout the different delivery success rates across the various carriers within the dataset.
  • The insignificant differences between the carriers suggest that delivery success rates do not depend on the carrier used. This means that whichever carrier is used by any individual does not statistically impose an impact on its delivery success.
  1. Shipment Cost and Speed
  • By a Correlation analysis, (Pearson r = .606, p < 0.05) there is an indicated strong positive relationship between the cost of shipment and its delivery speed.
  • This means that shipments that fall within the higher cost side will almost always be delivered faster than shipments that cost significantly less.
  1. Seasonal Effects
  • Statistically, by a Two-Way ANOVA test there was no significance between carriers (p = 0.927), seasons (p = 0.283), as well as the interaction between carriers & seasons (p = 0.549) which indicated consistency with performance across seasons.
  • Although, given the graph, we can visually attest to a shift in shipments decreasing for a particular carrier (Amazon) when approaching the winter.

Machine Learning Analysis and Visualization

Predicting Transit Days

Based on the previous EDA conclusion, a strong positive relationship between the cost of shipment and its delivery speed was noted. Understanding how long a shipment will take provides important information to stakeholders that can help with logistical decisions and planning on both sides. Potentially saving time and money and increasing efficiency.

  • Carrier Selection: Both customers and businesses are able to select carriers that are able to consistently fulfill the requirements of delivery speed for different shipment profiles (weight, distance, season, cost tier).

  • Operational Planning: When companies are able to predict transit time more reliably, they can allocate warehouse staff, loading resources, and delivery windows in a more efficient way.

  • Pricing Strategy: It is a common practice among carriers to charge more for faster deliveries. Predicting transit time gives businesses the opportunity to decide if the higher costs actually result in a significant saving of time.

Since transit speed has a direct influence on customer satisfaction and logistics costs, a predictive model for Transit Days is an excellent source of operational insights.

Feature Preparation and Train-Test Split

We set Transit_Days as the target for prediction and use all other categories as model features.

In[]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Target: Transit Days
y = df['Transit_Days']

# Use other factors as features
x = df.drop(["Shipment_ID", "Shipment_Date", "Delivery_Date", "Transit_Days"], axis = 1)

# 80 20 train - test
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Encoding categorical variables
X_train = pd.get_dummies(X_train, drop_first = True) # Drop a variable to prevent redundance
X_test = pd.get_dummies(X_test, drop_first = True)

# Joining for alignment
X_train, X_test = X_train.align(X_test, join = 'left', axis = 1)
X_test = X_test.fillna(0)

Model Choice: Random Forest Regressor

Random Forest Regression was chosen because it is appropriate for the structure of the dataset and the prediction task, especially due to the complexities of shipping logistics:

  • Handles nonlinear relationships: Transit time is influenced by complex interactions (e.g., distance weight, carrier season), which linear models often fail to capture.

  • Naturally supports categorical features: After one-hot encoding, Random Forests can meaningfully split on carrier, season, warehouse, and destination categories.

  • Resistant to outliers and noise: Since the dataset intentionally includes outliers and realistic variation, Random Forests ensemble averaging reduces sensitivity to extreme values.

  • Feature importance insight: Random Forests provide an interpretable ranking of the variables that most strongly influence transit daysvaluable for business decision-making.

In[]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor

# Create the random forest regressor
rf = RandomForestRegressor(
    n_estimators = 300,
    random_state = 42,
    n_jobs = -1
)

# fit the model with the data
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

Model Evaluation

We evaluate the model using common regression metrics:

  • R^2 Score (Coefficient of Determination)- How much variance in the target is explained by the model
  • MAE (Mean Absolute Error) - How many units the model's prediction is off by
  • RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error) - Square root of mean^2 errors, how big any errors are
In[]:
# Mean Absolute Error (Average Misses) and Mean Squared Error to detect how accurate model is predicting transit time
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score

predictions = rf.predict(X_test)

# Calculate each regression metric
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions)
mse = (mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions))
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, predictions)

print("R2 Score:", r2)
print("Mean Absolute Error:", mae)
print("Mean Squared Error:", mse)
print("Root Mean Squared Error:", rmse)

Model Performance Interpretation

  • R^2 score: 0.991 The model explains approximately 99.1% of the variation in transit days. This indicates an extremely strong fit and suggests that the features in the dataset provide substantial predictive power for estimating delivery time.

  • MAE: 0.071 days (1.7 hours) On average, the models predictions are extremely close to the actual transit duration.

  • RMSE: 0.185 days (4.4 hours) This confirms that even larger prediction errors are rare and remain within a practically acceptable window for logistics operations.

From a business perspective, this level of accuracy is highly valuable. A model that can consistently predict transit duration within a few hours can allow organizations to:

  • Improve delivery scheduling and warehouse staffing

  • Set more accurate customer delivery expectations

  • Estimate whether higher shipping costs meaningfully reduce transit time

  • Compare carrier performance under equivalent shipment conditions

Overall, the model performs well and provides reliable predictions that can be applied to real-world logistics planning.

Clustering

Clustering will help us identify natural shipment groups based on performance-related metrics. After running hypothesis tests and building predictive models, clustering provides a way to detect patterns in shipping behaviors and understand natural operational groups.

Similar to HW4, the process involves:

  • One-Hot encoding for categorical features
  • StandardScaler to scale features to prepare for clustering
  • KMeans to apply Elbow Method, identifying when adding clusters doesn't help variance anymore.
  • Within-Cluster sum of squares: minimize Intertia as described in Section 2.3.2 of Kmeans

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/clustering.html

Feature Engineering

To ensure meaningful clusters, we create features specifically tied to cost and performance. This improves interpretability and avoids poorly separated clusters.

In[]:
df = df.copy()

# Performance-focused features
df['Cost_per_mile'] = df['Cost'] / df['Distance_miles']
df['Transit_Distance_per_Day'] = df['Distance_miles'] / df['Transit_Days']

# Distance bins for "peer group"
df['distance_bin'] = pd.qcut(df['Distance_miles'], q=5, duplicates='drop')

# Median transit days per bin and deviation from that median
median_by_bin = (
    df.groupby('distance_bin', observed=True)['Transit_Days']
      .transform('median')
)
df.loc[:, 'Transit_Days_above_median'] = df['Transit_Days'] - median_by_bin

# Chosen feature set
cluster_features = ['Cost_per_mile',
                    'Transit_Distance_per_Day',
                    'Transit_Days_above_median']

cluster_df = df[cluster_features].copy()

Clustering Method:

  1. Scaling Features - since KMeans is distance based, it is important to scale features.
  2. Elbow method - we adapt the HW4 distortion score to compute mean distortion per point.
In[]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from yellowbrick.cluster import KElbowVisualizer
import yellowbrick.cluster.elbow as elbow_module
from yellowbrick.cluster.elbow import distortion_score

scaler = StandardScaler()
df_scaled_array = scaler.fit_transform(cluster_df)
df_scaled = pd.DataFrame(df_scaled_array, columns=cluster_features, index=cluster_df.index)

#Formatting off of HW4
def mean_distortion_score(X, labels, metric="euclidean"):
    """Compute the mean distortion (average squared distance to centroids)"""
    total_distortion = distortion_score(X, labels, metric)
    return total_distortion / X.shape[0]

elbow_module.KELBOW_SCOREMAP['distortion'] = mean_distortion_score

model = KMeans(random_state=42, n_init=10)

#Instantiate the KElbowVisualizer with the model and k range
visualizer = KElbowVisualizer(model, k=(1,11), metric='distortion', timings=False, locate_elbow=False)
visualizer.fit(df_scaled)
visualizer.show()
Out[]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'Mean Distortion Score Elbow for KMeans Clustering'}, xlabel='k', ylabel='mean distortion score'>

Silhouette Score Analysis

We use the silhouette score to accompany elbow method. The silhouette score measures similarity between and object and it's cluster compared to other clusters.

Main characteristics:

  • Higher scores indicate better-defined clusters.
  • Requires AT LEAST 2 clusters (range must start at 2)

Yellowbrick documentation here: https://www.scikit-yb.org/en/latest/api/cluster/silhouette.html

In[]:
from yellowbrick.cluster import SilhouetteVisualizer

# Choose a range of k values to evaluate
range_n_clusters = range(2, 8) # Silhouette score requires at least 2 clusters

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))

for i, k in enumerate(range_n_clusters):
    ax = plt.subplot(3, 3, i + 1) # Arrange plots in a grid

    # Instantiate the clustering model with a random state of 42 for reproducibility
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, init='k-means++', random_state=42, n_init=10)

    # Create a SilhouetteVisualizer instance with the KMeans model
    visualizer = SilhouetteVisualizer(model, colors='yellowbrick', ax=ax)

    # Fit to data and set titles
    visualizer.fit(df_scaled)
    ax.set_title(f'Silhouette Plot for k={k}')
    ax.set_xlabel('Silhouette coefficient values')
    ax.set_ylabel('Cluster label')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

K Decision: Both the elbow curve and the silhouette plots support k = 3 as a balanced option. The graph for k = 3 has the highest average silhouette score, and the clusters are wide and without many negative values, generally well-defined.

Final Clustering with K=3

In[]:
optimal_k = 3 # Chosen from on Elbow Method and Silhouette Score

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=optimal_k, init='k-means++', random_state=42, n_init=10)
df['Cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(df_scaled)

summary_features = cluster_features
cluster_summary = df.groupby('Cluster')[summary_features].mean()

print("Cluster Summary (Mean Performance Features):\n", cluster_summary)

Insights and Conclusion

This project focused on U.S. logistics performance by using statistical analysis and machine learning to discover how factors like carrier choice, shipment cost, distance, and seasonal timing impact delivery outcomes. By combining hypothesis testing, exploratory analysis, and predictive modeling, we discovered key drivers of transit efficiency.

Practical Recommendations for Shippers

One of the major insights that came from our data serve as actionable guidelines for businesses and individuals in charge of shipment planning:

  • Distance Is the Primary Driver of Transit Time

Our Random Forest model confirmed that distance is the main factor that delivery duration depends on. Shippers are advised to prioritize warehouses or distribution centers that are geographically closest to them.

  • Paying More Generally Improves Delivery Speed

Both Pearson correlation and cost-related feature importance show that fast delivery is associated with high-cost shipments. In this case, if the need for the shortest delivery is pressing, then a premium shipping tier or higher-priced services should be chosen.

  • Carrier Reliability Is Statistically Similar

The chi-square test indicates that delivery achievement rates are more or less the same across carriers. What this means is, at least in this dataset, carrier choice hardly causes shipment delivery success variation. Therefore, carrier choice can be based on other factors such as cost.

Carrier Insights

CostEfficiency Tradeoff

Although overall reliability is similar, we can see from the model that there are minor differences in speed that can change with seasons and vary from one carrier to another. Some carriers may regularly be able to run faster on certain routes or during specific times of the year; that the main reason behind the price increase is the downtick in the efficiency of the operations, optimization of the route, or priority handling; companies that are always shipping large volumes of products can get the most out of performance measurement at carrier-level through their shipment history by benchmarking.

Limitations of the Dataset

The dataset was sufficient to allow for a completed analysis. However, we should still take into account the limitations of the dataset:

  • Simulated Data

The dataset is completely fictional in terms of noise, outliers, and patterns, as it is not a real-world collection. Actual shipping behavior might be enveloped with additional complexities like weather disruptions, strikes, traffic conditions, or route-level constraints.

  • Limited Operational Variables

Some of the most critical logistics features, such as the mode of transport (air, ground), the number of transfer points, and the size of the package, are not accounted for. These factors could significantly affect delivery times.

  • Limited Time Span

The enhancement of shipment dates with multi-year data could facilitate the in-depth research of long-term seasonal trends or pandemic-level disruptions.

  • Uniform Carrier Behavior

The differences could be quite small between the performance of the actual shipping companies due to the balanced performance across carriers simulated in the dataset.

These drawbacks must be taken into consideration when using our findings in real logistics situations.

A classification model capable of identifying failed or delayed shipments would be an important source of practical information that could lead to risk reduction and higher customer satisfaction.

  • Clustering Shipment Patterns

Unsupervised learning (e.g., K-means or hierarchical clustering) may uncover hidden shipment archetypes, such as priority freight, regional routes, or weight-based categories, that determine delivery speed.

  • Time-Series Modeling

Time-series models (ARIMA, Prophet) application on a multi-year richer dataset may bring out seasonal cycles, holiday spikes, and long-term efficiency changes.

  • Route-Level Optimization Studies

The linkage of transit times with route geographies, weather APIs, or transportation network data may result in advanced logistics optimization.

Final Reflection

In essence, our research reveals the fact that carriers are almost equal when it comes to delivery success, but operational factors such as distance, cost, weight, and seasonal timing have a significant impact on transit speed. The excellent result of our predictive model is another proof of the importance of machine learning in logistics decision-making. With more data and additional features, these insights could go a long way to real-world shipping efficiency, planning accuracy, and customer satisfaction.
